5|$|Although {{not officially}} {{considered}} a <b>Sergeant</b> <b>Major</b> of the Marine Corps, when Archibald Sommers {{was appointed to}} the grade of <b>Sergeant</b> <b>Major</b> January 1, 1801, it was a solitary post, similar to the modern billet of <b>Sergeant</b> <b>Major</b> of the Marine Corps. In 1833, an act of legislation made the rank of <b>sergeant</b> <b>major</b> permanent for the Marine Corps and by 1899 five Marines held the rank of <b>sergeant</b> <b>major.</b> This continued until 1946, when the rank was abolished, only to be re-introduced in 1954 as part of the Marine Corps rank structure.|$|E
